text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!Varia]]%0a%0a!Power of Language in Surveys%0a%0a:Author: yuluz%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe choice of language in survey questions can have implicit biases that skew the responses.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn marketing class, we are taught to watch our language choice when designing surveys to avoid biases that would invalidate the results. One example the professor gave in class was Trump's Inaugural Year Approval Poll. The first question on the survey is:%0a%0aHow would you rate President Trump's first year in office(2017)?%0aOption 1: Great%0aOption 2: Good %0aOption 3: Okay%0aOption 4: Other%0a%0aThe available answer options only cover the positive half of the performance scale and skims over the negative half with the single choice "other". Even when respondents selected "other" and think that "other" means "bad", the survey maker could still argue that "other" is a neutral word and does not necessarily means "bad". %0a%0aIn contrast, the second question of the survey asks about Obama's performance and goes as follows:%0a%0aHow would you rate President Obama's first year in office(2009)?%0aOption 1: Great%0aOption 2: Good %0aOption 3: Okay%0aOption 4: Poor%0aOption 5: Other%0a%0aBy explicitly putting the option "poor" as one of the choices, the survey maker could make the fraudulent case like some people think Obama did poorly during his first year in office while nobody think Trump did poorly during the first year, so Trump is a better president.  %0a%0aHere is a news article talking about Trump's biased inaugural year approval poll: https://www.newsweek.com/trump-fake-poll-doesnt-let-americans-disapprove-white-house-764804%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210507-231610-337600#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-07.05.2021 - 16:16-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210507-231610-337600 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Connor_G%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a''''''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aThis is sometimes known as "response bias," and is one of many forms of potential biases that could (intentionally or unintentionally) skew the results of polls. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210507-231610-337600#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)
